  "why": "The TESTRNN fuzzer is designed under the assumption of producing semantically valid and realistic inputs and enforces this in multiple, domain-specific ways across fuzzing iterations. For discrete/sequential domains it uses semantics-preserving mutation functions (EDA for text; RDKit SMILES enumeration for molecules) that explicitly preserve meaning or molecular identity. For continuous domains it applies bounded Gaussian perturbations and rounds values to remain valid; generated mutants are tracked back to their original seed (orig mapping) and an oracle based on norm-balls (fixed radius around the original seed) is used to evaluate whether a mutant remains within a realistic/nearly-indistinguishable neighborhood of the seed. The tool also avoids semantically-invalid crossover and preserves parents in genetic search to prevent arbitrary drift. Together these choices enforce both semantic consistency and naturalness (i.e., realism) of inputs throughout the iterative test-generation process, matching the “High” definition (fixing or constraining semantically-critical content and controlling similarity relative to the original seed / plausible perturbation).",
  "evidence": "• Purpose / design emphasis on naturalness: \"...the consideration of the naturalness of input perturbation.\" (Abstract, p.1191). \n\n• Traceability to original seed (helps control similarity relative to original seed): \"It keeps the traceability of test cases via a mapping orig that maps each test case generated back to its seed origin.\" (Section VI, Algorithm 1, p.1196). \n\n• No semantically-invalid crossover and parent retention to limit drift: \"Crossover is trivial in our test case generation for RNNs... To avoid the validity issue, we skip this step and using mutation methods directly... The previous population is replaced with the new one. It should be noticed that the parents in the mating pool are also added to the new population to make sure that solutions are toward good directions during the iterations.\" (Section VI-B.2.c/d, p.1197). \n\n• Oracle / realism constraint defined relative to seed (norm-balls): \"We define a set of norm-balls, each of which is centered around a data sample with known label. The radius r_oracle... A test case x' is said to not pass the oracle if x' is within the norm-ball of some known sample x, i.e., ||x - x'||_2 <= r_oracle, and if x' has a different classification from x... a test case does not pass the oracle is an adversarial sample.\" (Section VI-C.1 Test Oracle, p.1198). \n\n• Text mutation preserves semantics / validity: \"The input to IMDB model is a sequence of words... we take a set M of mutants from the EDA toolkit... This ensures the mutated text paragraphs are always valid. In our experiments, we consider four mutation operations... The text meanings are reserved in all mutations.\" (Section VII-A.3 Input Mutation, p.1199--1200). \n\n• Molecular (SMILES) mutations preserve semantic identity: \"For Lipophilicity model, we take a set M of mutants that change the SMILES string without affecting the molecular structure it represents. The enumeration of possible SMILES for a molecule is implemented with the Python cheminformatics package RDKit... The enumerated SMILES strings are the test cases.\" (Section VII-A.3 Input Mutation, p.1199--1200). \n\n• Continuous-domain perturbations are small / constrained: \"When the LSTM input has continuous values (e.g., image input), Gaussian noises with fixed mean and variance are added to the input... For MNIST model, we add Gaussian noise to input image and round off the decimals around 0 and 1 to make the pixel value stay within the value range.\" (Section VI-B.2.1 Random Mutation and Section VII-A.3, p.1196 and p.1199). \n\n• Explicit statement of intent to preserve naturalness: \"...coverage-guided testing is to generate a set of test cases as diversified as possible while preserving the naturalness... Our diversified test cases are 'closer' to their seeds (points on the RNN’s data manifold), compared to other state-of-the-art tools, implying higher chance to be seen in the real-life operation, thus preserving the naturalness.\" (Introduction / Contributions, p.1192)."
